  abstract = {This research explores an innovative approach to Internet of Things circular economy through printed circuits on reusable steel substrates. We develop and characterize a manufacturing process for creating electronic circuits directly on steel surfaces using specialized conductive inks and insulation materials. Our evaluation involves fabricating and testing various IoT devices on steel substrates, measuring electrical performance, durability, and the ability to recover and reuse both the electronic components and the steel base material. The findings demonstrate that steel-based circuits can achieve competitive performance for many IoT applications while enabling straightforward component recovery and substrate reuse. Environmental impact assessment shows significant reductions in waste and energy consumption compared to conventional PCBs. We conclude that this approach represents a promising pathway for more sustainable IoT device manufacturing that aligns with circular economy principles while leveraging existing steel recycling infrastructure.},
